  "text": "do not depend on the circumference of the wedge. (4f) Therefore, the subtractions involved in renormalizing operators need to depend on the operators being renormalized only, and not on the size of the wedge state on which they are inserted. To achieve this last property, in [CITATION_1] , renormalization took two steps: in the first, the infinities were cancelled by subtracting the two-point function; in the second, the finite part of the two-point function (which depends on the width of the wedge) was compensated for. In contrast, we use the divergent part of the two-point function alone to compensate for the divergence and then study the impact of the finite part on the renormalization scheme, which means that in our approach, (4f) is automatically satisfied. In addition to these explicitly stated conditions, a very natural condition of translation invariance was also implied in [CITATION_2] .",
